Function COUNT

The COUNT function is a function in SQL that allows you to count the number of rows in a table that meet a certain condition.

id - title - release_year - genre - rating
1 - The Shawshank Redemption - 1994 - Drama - 9
2 - Tha Godfather - 1972 - Crime - 9
3 - The Godfather: Part II - 1974 - crime - 9
4 - The Dark Knight - 2008 - Action - 9
5 - 12 Angry Men - 1957 - Drama - 8
6 - Schindlers List - 1993 - Biography - 8
7 - Pulp Fiction - 1994 - Crime - 8
8 - The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King - 2003 - Adventure - 8
9 - Fight Club - 1999 - Drama - 8
10 - The Good, the Bad and the Ugly - 1966 - Western - 8

Here are some examples of how you can use the COUNT function in SQL

To count the number of rows in a table, you can use the following query:
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM movies;

This will return the total number of rows in the table.

COUNT(*)
10

To count the number of rows in a table where a certain column has a specific value, you can use the following query:
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM movies WHERE genre = 'Action';

this will return the number of rows in the table where the value of the genre column is Action.
COUNT(*)
1

To count the number of distinct values in a column, you can use the following query:
SELECT  COUNT(DISTINCT genre) FROM movies;

This will return the number of unique values in the genre column.
COUNT(DISTINCT genre)
6
